const a = [
  {"id":4679,"text":"A 50-year-old man presents to the emergency room with severe abdominal pain referred to the upper back and left shoulder along with nausea and vomiting. Pain is not relieved by nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs). He has a long history of alcohol abuse. The physician is suspecting acute pancreatitis. Which of the following findings is most likely to be present in the patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 115.","responses":[{"text":"Raised serum transaminases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised serum gastrin levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raised serum amylase levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool for occult blood positive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcifications on ultrasound abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4760,"text":"Which of the following nerves supplies the dermatome that is involved in referring the pain from the appendix to the umbilical region?","explanation":null,"reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 48.","responses":[{"text":"3rd cervical nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5th cranial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4th thoracic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7th thoracic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10th thoracic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5099,"text":"A 45-year-old man with a duodenal ulcer was treated with a combination of drugs intended to heal the mucosal damage and to eradicate Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori). Which of the following antibacterial drugs is used commonly to eradicate this organism?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 541.","responses":[{"text":"Ceftriaxone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciprofloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clindamycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cefazolin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clarithromycin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5109,"text":"Intestinal chyme stimulates the gastric secretion of about 10% of the acid in response to the meal. This early intestinal phase of stomach secretion is stimulated by which of the following?","explanation":"The early intestinal phase of stomach secretion is stimulated by **gastrin**. When chyme enters the duodenum, the presence of amino acids and peptides, in particular, stimulates the G cells in the duodenum to release gastrin, which then promotes further gastric acid secretion in the stomach.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSecretin is released in response to the acidic chyme in the duodenum. Its main role is to stimulate the pancreas to release bicarbonate-rich pancreatic juice, which neutralizes the acidic chyme. It does not stimulate gastric acid secretion; in fact, it inhibits it.\r\n\r\nAmino acids can stimulate gastrin release, but the primary stimulant for the early intestinal phase is gastrin itself.\r\n\r\nThe presence of fats in the duodenum stimulates the release of cholecystokinin (CCK) and secretin, which are involved in fat digestion and neutralizing stomach acid, respectively. They don't promote gastric acid secretion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 814.","responses":[{"text":"Gastrin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Amino acids in duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fat in duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reverse enterogastric reflex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5110,"text":"Which of the following syndromes represent the syndrome of iron deficiency anemia, glossitis, and dysphagia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 652.","responses":[{"text":"Plummer-Vinson syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Klinefelter syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Turner syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Down syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reiter’s syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5133,"text":"A 39-year-old woman presents with complaints of intermittent attacks of mild diarrhea, fever, and abdominal pain spaced by an asymptomatic period lasting for weeks to months. On physical examination, there are no remarkable findings. GI endoscopy reveals a thick rubbery intestinal wall. In addition, the radiography shows a string sign. Biopsies are performed in this region. Which of the following is the most classical finding of this condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 799.","responses":[{"text":"Skip lesion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophage-laden lamina propria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crypt abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crypt distortion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flask-shaped ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5134,"text":"Cardiac arrest and small bowel ulcers are the main nutritional toxicity symptoms of which essential macro-mineral?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Kose N, Bilgin F. Successful treatment of a patient with cardiac arrest due to hyperkalemia by prolonged cardiopulmonary resuscitation along with hemodialysis: a case report and review of the literature. Medicina. Published August 7, 2021. Accessed July 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8400023/\r\n (2) Han J, Lee SH, Giebisch G, Wang T. Potassium channelopathies and gastrointestinal ulceration. Gut and Liver. Published November 2016. Accessed July 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5087926/","responses":[{"text":"Chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphrous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5135,"text":"Deterioration of food (rancidity) is due to the presence of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ali M, Imran M, Nadeem M, et al. Oxidative stability and Sensoric acceptability of functional fish meat product supplemented with plant−based polyphenolic optimal extracts. Lipids in Health and Disease. Published January 31, 2019. Accessed July 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6357494/","responses":[{"text":"Esters","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tocopherols","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroxidants","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenolic compounds","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5185,"text":"A patient with a history of arthritis for the last nine years develops hematemesis. What is the most common cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 760,761.","responses":[{"text":"Esophageal varices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory-Weiss tear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric erosion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal cancer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5213,"text":"A 3-month-old male baby was brought to the outpatient department (OPD) with effortless spitting. The mother gave the history of on and off vomiting since 2nd week of life. On examination, weight was found to be 5 kg. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Leung AK, Hon KL. Gastroesophageal reflux in children: an updated review. Drugs in Context. Published June 17, 2019. Accessed January 29, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6586172/","responses":[{"text":"Gastroesophageal reflux disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyloric stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal stricture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tracheoesophageal fistula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hiatus hernia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5215,"text":"A 28-year-old male patient presents to the emergency department with painful swelling 2 cm above the umbilicus. The swelling is well-defined and mushroom-shaped. On examination, cough impulse is negative, the umbilicus is usual in appearance and inverted. A diagnosis of a ventral hernia is made. Which one of the following can not be a hernia content in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 777.","responses":[{"text":"Small bowel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendix","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Omentum only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preperitoneal fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large bowel","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5336,"text":"The increase in blood glucose after a test dose of carbohydrate compared with that after an equivalent amount of glucose is known as:","explanation":null,"reference":"Vlachos D, Malisova S, Lindberg FA, Karaniki G. Glycemic index (Gi) or glycemic load (Gl) and dietary interventions for optimizing postprandial hyperglycemia in patients with t2 diabetes: a review. Nutrients. Published May 27, 2020. Accessed July 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7352659/","responses":[{"text":"Blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycosylation Index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycemic load","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycemic index","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA1c","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5337,"text":"Which one of the following is not a manifestation of shaken baby syndrome?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 332.","responses":[{"text":"Spalding sign","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Subdural hematoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinal hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rib fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Burns","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5408,"text":"Which of the following is true for the investigations in a case of suspected intussusception?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"At ultrasonography, a doughnut sign on longitudinal section is diagnostic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At ultrasonography, a pseudo kidney sign on transverse section is diagnostic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these are true","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal radiograph is a first line investigation to confirm the diagnosis of intussusception","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasonography can predict irreducibility of intussusception using pneumatic reduction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5409,"text":"The patient accidentally took fluid, which was stored in Pepsi Cola’s bottle. He has started passing orange-colored urine, this can be due to poisoning from:","explanation":null,"reference":"Picric acid. Accessed July 9, 2022. https://webwiser.nlm.nih.gov/substance?substanceId=102\u0026identifier=Picric%20acid\u0026identifierType=name\u0026menuItemId=69\u0026catId=79","responses":[{"text":"Picric acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrochloric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbolic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphuric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitric acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5410,"text":"A 45-year-old male with a known case of hepatitis C develops hematemesis. He also has ascites. What is the most common cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 756,757.","responses":[{"text":"Esophagus carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory-Weiss tear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acid peptic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal varices","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5411,"text":"A 48-year-old female patient is brought to the emergency department with complaints of severe epigastric pain for 1 day, which became generalized and more severe for 3 hours. The pain is associated with vomiting, and she cannot tolerate even a liquid diet. She has a history of NSAID use for osteoarthritis for a long time. Her pulse is 120 beats/min, her blood pressure (BP) is 100/60 mmHg, she is afebrile, and her respiratory rate is 32 breaths/min. She has a tense tender abdomen with board-like rigidity. Gut sounds are inaudible. What is the most likely diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis in this patient is **perforated peptic ulcer**. The clinical picture of the patient, including sudden severe pain, **history of NSAID use**, vomiting, inability to tolerate oral intake, and especially the physical examination findings of a rigid, \"board-like\" abdomen with absent gut sounds, suggests a **perforation of the gastrointestinal tract leading to peritonitis**. Peptic ulcers, especially in the setting of prolonged NSAID use, can perforate, leading to the leakage of gastric or duodenal contents into the peritoneal cavity. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Perforated gallbladder** typically presents with right upper quadrant pain and not generalized abdominal pain with board-like rigidity. \r\n\r\nWhile the patient does likely have an underlying peptic ulcer (given her history of NSAID use), the acute presentation with the rigidity of the abdomen is more consistent with a perforated peptic ulcer rather than just a peptic ulcer.\r\n\r\n**Acute cholecystitis** usually presents with right upper quadrant pain that may radiate to the right shoulder, often triggered by a fatty meal.\r\n\r\n**Acute pancreatitis** condition can cause severe epigastric pain radiating to the back and may be associated with nausea and vomiting. The abdomen is usually tender but not rigid like in perforation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 766, 767.","responses":[{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated peptic ulcer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptic ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated gallbladder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5412,"text":"What is true for the pugilistic attitude of a dead body?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 270.","responses":[{"text":"It occurs in antemortem burns only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It does not occur in burns","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It occurs in postmortem burns only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is temporary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It may occur in both antemortem and postmortem burns","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5413,"text":"Prolong prothrombin time occurs in case of poisoning with:","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 280.","responses":[{"text":"Parathion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead arsenate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraquat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Zinc sulphide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5415,"text":"Biopsy of a small and rounded rectal polyp demonstrates glands and saw tooth crypts composed of a proliferation of goblet and columnar epithelial cells. No atypia is seen. This polyp is best classified as which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 804.","responses":[{"text":"Peutz-Jeghers polyp","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubulovillous adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubular adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Villous adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperplastic polyp","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5416,"text":"A 45-year-old male patient was diagnosed with peptic ulcer for the last 1 year and is on maintenance therapy with antacid along with histamine (H2) receptor blocker. Recently, the patient came to the gastroenterology outpatient department (OPD)  with concern that his cardiologist asked him to choose an alternative option for H2 receptor blocker because prescribed H2 receptor blocker can affect the metabolism of other prescribed drugs. Which histamine H2 blocker has the most marked inhibitory effect on microsomal cytochrome P-450 enzyme?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Famotidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Roxatidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loratadine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cimetidine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ranitidine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5417,"text":"Which of the following is the most common benign salivary gland tumor?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 744.","responses":[{"text":"Basal cell adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleomorphic adenoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Canalicular adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warthin’s tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oncocytoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5429,"text":"A 50-year-old male smoker was diagnosed with peritonitis secondary to a perforated duodenal ulcer. The most likely organisms found in this patient:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 817.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klebsiella pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli \u0026 Bacteroides","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5430,"text":"In which of the following transitional stage in demography, both birth, and death rates are low. Birth rates may drop to well below replacement level as has happened in some of the European countries. What demographic stage could it be?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture Slides: Gastrointestinal-II, Community Medicine, Topic: Demography Lecture 1.","responses":[{"text":"Stage one","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage three","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage four","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage two","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage five","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5431,"text":"A formal statement of the nutrition goals and interventions prescribed for an individual using the data obtained from a nutrition assessment is termed as:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kim EM, Baek HJ. A survey on the status of nutrition care process implementation in Korean hospitals. Clinical Nutrition Research. Published July 2013. Accessed July 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3728464/","responses":[{"text":"Nutrient requirement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutrition care plan","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutrition therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutritional assessment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutrient formulation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5432,"text":"A 9-month-old female baby weighing 8 kg is brought to the emergency department with the complaint of loose motions for the last 3 days. On examination, the baby is irritable and her eyes are sunken. She is eager to drink and her skin pinch goes back slowly. What is the most likely diagnosis according to the IMNCI protocol?","explanation":null,"reference":"Diarrhoea and Dehydration. World Health Organization; 2008. Accessed July 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK143745/","responses":[{"text":"Mild dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Some dehydration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shock","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5436,"text":"A 54-year-old man presents with 5 months of upper abdominal pain accompanied by nausea. He does not have hematemesis. Physical examination is unremarkable, and laboratory workup reveals stool sample positive for occult blood. Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy is performed, and gastric biopsies are taken. On microscopic examination, they reveal acute and chronic mucosal inflammation along with the presence of Helicobacter pylori organisms. The presence of these organisms is most likely to be associated with which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 766.","responses":[{"text":"Pernicious anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal peptic ulceration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diffuse large B cell lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypochlorhydria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric mucosal invasion with septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5438,"text":"A 50-year-old male develops melena. What could be the probable cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 756.","responses":[{"text":"Rectal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acid peptic disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectal ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory bowel disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5439,"text":"A 10-year-old female child weighing 30 kg was brought to you with complaints of fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, passing dark urine, and clay-colored stools for the last 3 days. The most likely diagnosis is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Schaefer TJ, John S. Acute hepatitis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 12, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551570/","responses":[{"text":"Acute glomerulonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute viral hepatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5440,"text":"The type of additive required in foods containing fats and oils to prevent rancidity is called:","explanation":null,"reference":"Taghvaei M, Jafari SM. Application and stability of natural antioxidants in edible oils in order to substitute synthetic additives. Journal of Food Science and Technology. Published March 2015. Accessed July 11, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4348291/","responses":[{"text":"Preservatives","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Free radical producers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Solvents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emulsifiers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antioxidants","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5441,"text":"During absorption of carbohydrates, a transporter that transports glucose and galactose against their concentration gradients is used, which is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 831.","responses":[{"text":"GLUT5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SGLT1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5442,"text":"A 45-year-old man has had vague abdominal pain and nausea for the past 3 years. This pain is unrelieved by antacid medications. He has no difficulty swallowing and no heartburn following meals. On physical examination, there are no abnormal findings. Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy reveals antral mucosal erythema, but no ulcerations or masses. Biopsies are taken, and microscopically there is chronic non-specific gastritis. Which of the following conditions is most likely to be present in this man?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 763.","responses":[{"text":"Helicobacter pylori infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pernicious anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zollinger-Ellison syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5443,"text":"95% of cancers of the head and neck are:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 731.","responses":[{"text":"Nasopharyngeal angiofibroma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraganglioma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neuroblastomas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasopharyngeal carcinomas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinomas","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5446,"text":"A patient with Crohn’s disease presented to emergency with complaints of absolute constipation and vomiting. A short narrowing is noted in the mid transverse colon. What would be the most likely option to treat his condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Steroid therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stoma formation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extended left hemicolectomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stricturoplasty","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Extended right hemicolectomy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5453,"text":"In severe upper gastrointestinal bleed, the patient has:","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 157, 293.","responses":[{"text":"Hypertension and bradycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension and tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypotension and tachycardia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypotension and bradycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normotensive","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5454,"text":"Which of the following is not safe in patients with celiac disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Campbell JA. Foods for patients with celiac disease. Can Med Assoc J. 1982;127(10):963-965. Accessed July 11, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1862315/","responses":[{"text":"Rice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vegetable","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barley","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fruits","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meat","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5455,"text":"A 60-year-old-female presented with abdominal pain and weight loss. Her ultrasound shows lesions in the liver. What is the next appropriate investigation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 854.","responses":[{"text":"Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography (PTC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plain X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radionuclide imaging","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5456,"text":"A 27-year-old man is brought to the emergency room for trauma to head from a fight. Upon examination, there is a swelling in the right temporal region. X-ray shows a fracture of the skull without displacement, the injury will be declared as:","explanation":null,"reference":"Pakistan penal code. Accessed August 3, 2022. https://pljlawsite.com/html/ppc337a.htm","responses":[{"text":"Shajjah ammah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah khafifa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah munaqillah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah hashimah","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah damigah","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5457,"text":"The study of quantifiable characteristics of a population is defined as demography. The demographic equation is represented by the sum of:","explanation":null,"reference":"17. 2b: three demographic variables. Social Sci LibreTexts. Published August 22, 2018. Accessed August 3, 2022. https://socialsci.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Sociology/Introduction_to_Sociology/Book%3A_Sociology_(Boundless)/17%3A_Population_and_Urbanization/17.02%3A_Population_Growth/17.2B%3A_Three_Demographic_Variables","responses":[{"text":"Net migration and natural change","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Net migration and dependency ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Net migration and crude death rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nature change and dependency ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Net migration and crude birth rate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5475,"text":"Neonates who are nutritionally at risk may have birth weight less than:","explanation":null,"reference":"Cutland CL, Lackritz EM, Mallett-Moore T, et al. Low birth weight: Case definition \u0026 guidelines for data collection, analysis, and presentation of maternal immunization safety data. Vaccine. Published December 4, 2017. Accessed July 16, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5710991/","responses":[{"text":"3000 gm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1000 gm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2000 gm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2500 gm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1500 gm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5476,"text":"A patient has had arthritis for 10 years. He has been taking aspirin frequently. After a few months, he came to the outpatient department (OPD) with complaints of gastric pain, retrosternal burning, anorexia, and frequent vomiting. He was diagnosed with a case of aspirin induced peptic ulcer. What is the appropriate drug of choice for this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 543.","responses":[{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ranitidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium bicarbonate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Misoprostol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5477,"text":"The number of live births in a year in an area divided by mid-year female population 15-44 in the same area, multiplied by 1000. This is the formula to calculate:","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture Slides: Gastrointestinal module, Community Medicine slides, Topic: Measures of fertility and mortality.","responses":[{"text":"Age specific fertility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Net reproduction ratio","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gross reproduction rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Replacement level fertility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General fertility rate","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5599,"text":"Which of the following is not a feature of squamous cell carcinoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 716.","responses":[{"text":"Peripheral palisading of nuclei","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Disturbed architecture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperkeratosis or dyskeratosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Keratin pearls","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loss of Intercellular bridges","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5600,"text":"Energy expenditure necessary to maintain basic physiologic function under standardized condition(s) is called:","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 897.","responses":[{"text":"Energy equilibrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thermogenic effect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body mass index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optimum metabolic rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basal metabolic rate","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5601,"text":"A 41-year-old man has experienced progressive fatigue, pruritus, and jaundice for the past 4 months. He had a total colectomy performed five years ago. On physical examination, he is afebrile and scleral icterus is present. Cholangiography reveals the widespread obliteration of intrahepatic bile ducts. A liver biopsy is performed and microscopic examination shows periductular 'onion skin' fibrosis with a moderate lymphocytic infiltrate. Some intrahepatic bile ducts are obliterated, but there is no interface hepatitis. Which of the following underlying diseases is he most likely to have?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 860.","responses":[{"text":"Cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5602,"text":"A 38-year-old female patient came to the outpatient department with a complaint of recurrent diarrhea. She is suspected of having Crohn’s disease. A colonoscopy is planned to confirm the diagnosis. Which of the following will be observed in colonoscopy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 797.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseating granulomas will be seen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skip lesions are encountered","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of pseudo polyps","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Involvement of rectal mucosa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5603,"text":"Which of the following antibiotics is for the treatment of Whipple disease daily for 1 year (one year)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 809.","responses":[{"text":"Ceftriaxone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Co-trimoxazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clarithromycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5604,"text":"What is the confirmatory test for diagnosis of upper GI bleeding?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 775.","responses":[{"text":"Proctoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium meal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium enema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium swallow","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5605,"text":"A 54-year-old male presented to the emergency with complaints of severe pain in the abdomen, and bilious vomiting. There is a bulge about 8 cm lateral to the umbilicus in the line of linea semilunaris. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Huttinger R, Sugumar K, Baltazar-Ford KS. Spigelian hernia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 17, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538290/","responses":[{"text":"Richter’s hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spigelian hernia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Littre’s hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epigastric hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraumbilical hernia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5606,"text":"A 25-year-old patient is going on a journey with his friends, but he has motion sickness. Which of the following is a prophylactic therapy in his case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Spinks A, Wasiak J. Scopolamine (Hyoscine) for preventing and treating motion sickness. The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews. Published June 15, 2011. Accessed July 18, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7138049/","responses":[{"text":"Droperidol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclizine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyoscine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphenhydramine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aprepitant","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5607,"text":"“Undertakers Fracture” due to falling of head (backward) occurs at:","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 402.","responses":[{"text":"C5 – C6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C6 – C7","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"L5 – S1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T12 – L1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C1 – C2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5608,"text":"The gastrointestinal tract consists of mucosa, submucosa, muscularis externa, and adventitia. Which of the following germ layer give rise to the epithelium and glands of the mucosal layer?","explanation":null,"reference":"Bhatia A, Shatanof RA, Bordoni B. Embryology, gastrointestinal. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 18, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537172/","responses":[{"text":"Endoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Extraembryonic mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intraembryonic splanchnic mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intraembryonic somatic mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5609,"text":"Self-inflicted cuts are common and they are produced by the person himself or herself to produce false allegations or to neutralize the case. Which of the following is a feature of such wounds?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 206.","responses":[{"text":"Depth is usually deep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Site can be anywhere in body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arrangement is random","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tailing is absent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clothes are not involved","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5610,"text":"The body of a young female is brought to a mortuary and when it was examined by a female medico-legal officer, she decided it’s a homicidal cutthroat. One of the positive features of this was:","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 199.","responses":[{"text":"Depth of wound was maximum in the middle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hesitation cuts near the wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wound position high up in neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Defense wound absent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cadaveric spasm present","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5611,"text":"A male of 45 years was brought to a mortuary, features of suicidal cutthroat were visible, it includes:","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 199.","responses":[{"text":"Depth of wound maximum with middle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Defense wounds may be present","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wound position in middle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tailing is absent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hesitation cuts near the wound","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5616,"text":"A 50-year-old man has had persistent nausea for 5 years with occasional vomiting. On physical examination, there are no abnormal findings. He undergoes upper gastrointestinal (GI) endoscopy, which shows a small area of gastric fundal mucosa has loss of rugal folds. Biopsies are taken and microscopically reveal well-differentiated adenocarcinoma confined to the mucosa. An upper GI endoscopy performed 5 years previously showed a pattern of gastritis and microscopically there was chronic inflammation. Which of the following is the most likely risk factor for his neoplasm?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 771,772.","responses":[{"text":"Use of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helicobacter pylori infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic alcohol abuse","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inherited APC gene mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5618,"text":"A 32-year-old male patient, with a known case of Crohn’s disease, came to the outpatient department (OPD) with complaints of multiple discharging sinuses in the perianal region. What would be the most appropriate radiological investigation to reach the diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 774.","responses":[{"text":"Magnetic resonance imaging scan","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray abdomen supine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"WBC labelled scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray abdomen erect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5619,"text":"A 35-year-old lady presented to the outpatient department (OPD) with intermittent diarrhea, fever, and on and off abdominal pain. Biopsy of this patient shows deep ulcers, marked lymphoid reaction, fibrosis, serositis, granuloma mass, and fistulas. Which of the following is the most likely possibility?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 797, table 17-9.","responses":[{"text":"Malabsorption syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal polyposis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colorectal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5620,"text":"Which of the following is a common cause of anemia in small bowel bacterial overgrowth syndrome?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 645, table 14-5.","responses":[{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B12 deficiency anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia of chronic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folate deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5622,"text":"A 37-year-old man complains of chest pain after meals. He says this pain has gone on for a few months and gets only minimal relief from antacid tablets. The physician prescribes a drug that will decrease the amount of acid secreted by binding to and inhibiting an ATPase on the lumenal surface of parietal cells. Which of the following drugs works by inhibiting the ATPase enzyme?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 543.","responses":[{"text":"Atropine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Octreotide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Misoprostol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cimetidine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5624,"text":"Volvulus is an abnormal rotation of the intestinal loop (midget), which results in twisting and compromised blood supply of the intestinal loop. Normal rotation of midgut loop is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Alani M, Rentea RM. Midgut malrotation. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 18, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560888/","responses":[{"text":"270 degree clockwise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"270-degree counterclockwise","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"180-degree counterclockwise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"90-degree counterclockwise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"90 degree clockwise","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5628,"text":"A 45-year-old man was diagnosed with hepatitis B infection 2 years ago. Now he came to the outpatient department (OPD) for the follow-up. Recovery from hepatitis B infection is indicated by which of the following negative test?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 873.","responses":[{"text":"Anti-HBc","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-HBs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBeAg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBsAg","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HBcAg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5629,"text":"Three weeks after a meal at a roadside restaurant, a 20-year-old male presents with loss of appetite, malaise, fatigue, and mild yellowness of sclera. Which of the following laboratory test findings is he most likely to have?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 872.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis B surface antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis D IgM antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B core antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis A IgM antibody","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis C antibody","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5630,"text":"A 3-year-old child was given one tablet three times a day to control loose motions. The diarrhea stopped but the next day the child was brought in a toxic condition with abdominal distention and vomiting. He had paralytic ileus, mild dehydration, low blood pressure, and sluggish reflexes. Which antidiarrheal drug could have caused this condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 548.","responses":[{"text":"Furazolidone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodochlorhydroxyquinoline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loperamide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metronidazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ondansetron","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5631,"text":"A week-old female baby, weighing 3.5 kg, on breast milk feeding, was brought to the outpatient department (OPD) with complaints of yellow discoloration of skin and sclera for the last one week. The baby is passing dark yellow urine and clay-colored stool. On examination, the baby looks well but the liver is grossly enlarged. The most likely diagnosis is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 559.","responses":[{"text":"Neonatal hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"G-6PD deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen storage disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breast milk jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital biliary atresia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5632,"text":"The salivary secretion from the salivary glands contains different ions. When it is compared with plasma, the saliva has:","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 809.","responses":[{"text":"More of sodium chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less concentration of NaCl","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Less concentration of HCO3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less concentration of K+","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More concentration of H+","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5635,"text":"Total protein requirement in critical care patients is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Deer RR, Volpi E. Protein requirements in critically ill older adults. Nutrients. Published March 20, 2018. Accessed July 20, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5872796/","responses":[{"text":"0.6-0.8 gm/Kg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.8 – 2.0 gm/Kg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"– 2.0 gm/Kg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.5-1.0 gm/Kg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1.2 – 1.8 gm/Kg","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5636,"text":"Treatment for parathyroid hyperplasia is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Tonelli F, Giudici F, Cavalli T, Brandi ML. Surgical approach in patients with hyperparathyroidism in multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1: total versus partial parathyroidectomy. Clinics. Published April 2012. Accessed July 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3328832/","responses":[{"text":"Removal of all four glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Removal of 3 and half glands","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No treatment required","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enlarged glands to be removed","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5641,"text":"A 30-year-old male is brought to the emergency department with the complaint of shifting pain in the right lower abdomen for 2 days, which has become severe and generalized to the whole abdomen since morning. He is febrile, has three episodes of vomiting, and is unable to take orally. His pulse is 110 b/min, blood pressure (BP) is 100/70 mmHg, temperature is 100F. He has a tense tender abdomen on palpation with absent bowel sounds. What is the most likely cause of his condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Jones MW, Lopez RA, Deppen JG. Appendicitis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 20, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK493193/","responses":[{"text":"Perforated appendix","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Perforated peptic ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5645,"text":"A 53-year-old woman presents with complaints of weakness, anorexia, malaise, constipation, and back pain. While being evaluated, she becomes somewhat lethargic. Laboratory studies include a normal chest x-ray, serum albumin 3.2 mg/dL, serum calcium 14 mg/dL, serum phosphorus 2.6 mg/dL, serum chloride 108 mg/dL, blood urea nitrogen (BUN) 32 mg/dL, and creatinine 2.0 mg/dL. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","explanation":null,"reference":"Tonog P, Lakhkar AD. Normal saline. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 23, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545210/","responses":[{"text":"Administration of intravenous phosphorus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous normal saline infusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Administration of thiazide diuretics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck exploration and parathyroidectomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Use of mithramycin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5646,"text":"Healthy carrier state is indicated by positivity for which of the following in HBV infected patients for more than 6 months?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 836, table 18-3.","responses":[{"text":"HBV DNA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBcAg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-HBcAg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBsAg","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HBeAg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5647,"text":"A 23-year-old male is brought to the emergency department with the complaint of pain in right lower abdomen for 5 days, which increases after eating. He has off and on diarrhea, with a history of weight loss for 3 months. He is also having intermittent fever for a few weeks. His pulse is 110 b/min, blood pressure (BP) is 100/70 mmHg and temperature is 100F. On examination, there is a tender palpable mass in the right iliac fossa absent bowel sounds. He also has two discharging fistulas in the peri-anal region. A complete blood picture was performed which depicts hemoglobin (Hb) of 8 gm/dl. What is the most likely cause of his condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 799.","responses":[{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn’s disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5648,"text":"The combination of ethanol and disulfiram results in nausea and hypertension as a result of the accumulation of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 599.","responses":[{"text":"Methanol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetaldehyde","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"NADH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyruvate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5649,"text":"A 48-year-old female patient is brought to the emergency department (ER) with complaints of severe epigastric pain for 1 day, which became generalized and more severe for 3 hours. Pain is associated with vomiting and even she is unable to tolerate a liquids diet. She has a history of NSAIDs use for osteoarthritis for a long period of time. Her pulse is 120 breaths/min, blood pressure (BP) is 100/60 mmHg, the temperature is afebrile and respiratory rate of 32 breath/min. She has a tense tender abdomen with board-like rigidity. Gut sounds inaudible. What would be the most appropriate radiological investigation to reach the diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 787.","responses":[{"text":"X-ray abdomen supine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray abdomen erect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI Abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5650,"text":"A 34-year-old man presents in the gastrointestinal (GI) clinic with abdominal pain, and jaundice. His laboratory investigation confirms that he is positive for hepatitis C infection. Which of the following is true of hepatitis C infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 834.","responses":[{"text":"Infection is common in women","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha-interferon is an effective treatment to cure the infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Persistent infection and chronic hepatitis are the hall marks of the infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis C virus is a DNA virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Commonly transmitted by sexual contact","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5651,"text":"Regarding the microscopic picture of pyogenic granuloma, which of the following is true?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 728.","responses":[{"text":"Shallow hyperemic ulcerations with predominantly mononuclear inflammatory infiltrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nodular mass of fibrous tissue with few inflammatory cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aggregation of multinucleated giant cells separated by highly vascular stroma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lobulated masses of capillary sized vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epithelioid granuloma with multinucleated giant cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5652,"text":"A patient returning from a dinner party meets with a road accident and has to be urgently operated upon under general anesthesia. Which of the following drug can be injected intramuscularly to hasten his gastric emptying?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 176.","responses":[{"text":"Promethazine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atropine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoclopramide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Apomorphine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylpolysiloxane","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5653,"text":"A 43-year-old man has had mid-epigastric pain and nausea for the past 2 months. On physical examination, he has no abnormal findings. On upper GI endoscopy, a solitary sharply demarcated 2-cm shallow gastric antral ulcer is seen. Which of the following laboratory test findings is most likely to be present in this man?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 763,764.","responses":[{"text":"Increased plasma cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric achlorhydria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated serum gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive urea breath test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive serology for antinuclear antibody","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5654,"text":"Which of the following infection is associated with nasopharyngeal carcinoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 360.","responses":[{"text":"Amoebic infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Candidal infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Helicobacter pylori infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Human papillomavirus (HPV) infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5655,"text":"A 45-year-old patient diagnosed with Parkinson's disease and currently on maintenance therapy with levodopa. Although his symptoms are well controlled with levodopa, but major disturbing side effects are nausea and vomiting. The physician decided to start an antiemetic that did not affect the antiparkinsonian activity of levodopa. Which of the following antiemetic selectively blocks levodopa-induced vomiting without blocking its antiparkinsonian action?","explanation":null,"reference":"Lertxundi U, Domingo-Echaburu S, Soraluce A, García M, Ruiz-Osante B, Aguirre C. Domperidone in Parkinson’s disease: a perilous arrhythmogenic or the gold standard? Current Drug Safety. Published February 2013. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23656449/","responses":[{"text":"Ondansetron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Domperidone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoclopramide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cisapride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aprepitant","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5656,"text":"Dry burn is caused by:","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 274, table 14.5","responses":[{"text":"Deep X-rays","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Strong acid or alkalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flame or hot metals","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultraviolent rays","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hot liquid or steam","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5657,"text":"A 30-year-old female developed bleeding after excessive bouts of vomiting. The bleeding stopped spontaneously. Upper GI endoscopy showed longitudinal mucosal lacerations in the lower part of the esophagus. What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Mallory-Weiss tears** are characterized by **longitudinal mucosal lacerations** in the lower part of the esophagus and occasionally the upper part of the stomach, typically at the **gastroesophageal junction**. They are often associated with **bouts of severe vomiting** and can result in hematemesis (vomiting of blood). The condition is self-limiting in many cases, with bleeding stopping spontaneously.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhile esophageal cancer can present with bleeding, it does not typically arise after episodes of vomiting. The primary symptoms are dysphagia (difficulty swallowing), unintentional weight loss, and often, a longer history of symptoms.\r\n\r\nEsophageal erosions refer to superficial breaks in the esophageal mucosa, usually seen in conditions like gastroesophageal reflux disease. They can cause pain or discomfort but are not typically associated with severe vomiting and hematemesis.\r\n\r\nGastric varices are dilated veins in the stomach that can bleed, but they aren't typically associated with episodes of vomiting. They are more common in the setting of portal hypertension, such as in cirrhosis.\r\n\r\nLike gastric varices, esophageal varices are dilated veins, this time in the esophagus. They can bleed, especially if ruptured, and are also associated with portal hypertension. However, the association with vomiting and the endoscopic findings differentiate Mallory-Weiss tears from esophageal varices.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 754.","responses":[{"text":"Esophageal varices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal erosions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric varices","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory Weiss tears","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5658,"text":"A 3-week-old boy is referred for persistent vomiting. He was well until 5 days ago but is now vomiting after each feed, is not putting on weight, and appears jaundiced. After a test, he has a projectile non-bilious vomit. You suspect that he has pyloric stenosis and perform a venous gas and electrolyte analysis. What would you expect the result to reveal","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 801.","responses":[{"text":"Hypochloraemic metabolic alkalosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No derangement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperchloraemic metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperchloraemic metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypochloraemic metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5659,"text":"Foods that have a low glycemic index are considered to be more beneficial because they cause less fluctuation in the secretion of:","explanation":null,"reference":"Holesh JE, Aslam S, Martin A. Physiology, carbohydrates. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 14, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459280/","responses":[{"text":"Insulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucocorticoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5660,"text":"A 50-year-old male with a history of ischemic heart disease presents with blood in the vomitus. There is no history of NSAIDs or steroid use. On examination, there is splenomegaly, ascites, and caput medusa around the umbilicus. Considering the diagnosis, what will be the best treatment option?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 304.","responses":[{"text":"Octreotide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"I/V proton pump inhibitors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral proton pump inhibitors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terlipressin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fluid resuscitation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5661,"text":"A 20-year-old man is healthy but has a family history of colon cancer with onset at a young age. There are no abnormal physical examination findings. He undergoes colonoscopy and there are over 200 tubular adenomas ranging in size from 0.2 to 1 cm on gross inspection and microscopic examination of biopsies. Which of the following genetic diseases is he most likely to have?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 809.","responses":[{"text":"Hereditary non-polyposis colon carcinoma syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gardner syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenomatous polyposis coli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple endocrine neoplasia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5662,"text":"A 13-year-old child with a history of type 1 diabetes mellitus presents with intermittent diarrhea, abdominal pain, and vomiting. On examination, he has short stature with anemia, angular stomatitis, and paresthesia. What is the likely clinical diagnosis?","explanation":"**Celiac disease**, also known as gluten-sensitive enteropathy, is an **autoimmune condition** where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. Clinical features can include chronic diarrhea, abdominal pain, vomiting, short stature due to malabsorption, anemia, and other signs of nutrient deficiencies like angular stomatitis. The coexistence of type-1 diabetes mellitus and celiac disease is also well-recognized, as both conditions have an autoimmune etiology. \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)** can cause abdominal pain and altered bowel habits, but it would not explain the anemia, short stature, or other specific symptoms mentioned.\r\n\r\n**Diabetic neuropathy** results from long-term high blood sugar levels and primarily affects the nerves, causing symptoms like numbness and pain. However, it would not account for the gastrointestinal symptoms or the anemia and angular stomatitis described.\r\n\r\n**Hypopituitarism** refers to decreased secretion of one or more of the pituitary hormones, leading to various symptoms depending on the hormone(s) affected. While it could cause growth issues, it would not typically present with the gastrointestinal symptoms mentioned.\r\n\r\n**Chronic giardiasis** is a parasitic infection that can cause diarrhea and abdominal pain, but it would not typically lead to the full spectrum of symptoms like angular stomatitis or the strong association with type-1 diabetes mellitus.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 783.","responses":[{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypopituitarism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetic neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5664,"text":"A 44-year-old man, an emergency medical technician, has felt fatigued for the past 4 months. On physical examination, there are no remarkable findings. Laboratory studies show his alanine transaminase (ALT) 132 U/L and aspartate transaminase (AST) 113 U/L with total bilirubin 1.3 mg/dL and direct bilirubin 0.8 mg/dL. A liver biopsy is performed, and microscopic examination shows focal necrosis, interface inflammation with the extension of inflammation into the lobules from the triads. There is a ground-glass appearance of hepatocytes. Which of the following laboratory test findings is most characteristic for his disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 836, 837.","responses":[{"text":"Positive anti hepatitis B surface antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive delta antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive anti hepatitis B core antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive HCV RNA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive hepatitis B surface antigen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5665,"text":"A 22-year-old girl develops severe retching with nausea and vomiting. She later has hematemesis of about 200 ml. Which of the following is the most probable cause of hematemesis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 754.","responses":[{"text":"Gastroesophageal reflux disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory Weiss tear","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5666,"text":"Hair singeing is present in:","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 274.","responses":[{"text":"Dry heat","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dry and moist both","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical injuries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Moist heat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No hair singing in present in burns","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5667,"text":"which of the following is correct regarding the postmortem appearance of arsenic poisoning, when dead body cavities are opened on the autopsy table:","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Stomach contents shows white particles floating","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhages in all viscera of body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach shows red velvety appearance","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Capillaries of gastrointestinal are of normal appearance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver and kidney show congestion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5668,"text":"A 25-year-old male presents to the emergency with severe abdominal pain radiating to the back and left shoulder for 24 hours. He has a history of anorexia and vomiting for two days. What is the most likely diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 887.","responses":[{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5669,"text":"A 26-year-old man suffered a heavy blow on the chin in boxing after which there was the escape of blood and cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) from the nose, and extravasation of blood in the orbit which manifested as a \"black eye\". Which type of fracture could have led to this?","explanation":"A **fracture through the anterior cranial fossa** can be associated with a blow to the chin or frontal region. The fracture typically extends through the ethmoid bone, and patients may present with a **\"raccoon eye\" or \"black eye\"** due to blood accumulation in the orbit. CSF rhinorrhea, or the leakage of CSF from the nose, can also occur due to damage to the cribriform plate.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nGutter fracture is a linear skull fracture that runs parallel to the major suture lines.\r\n\r\nFracture through the middle cranial fossa could potentially result in CSF otorrhea (leakage of CSF from the ear) and may damage the facial or auditory nerves.\r\n\r\nFracture through the posterior cranial fossa can be associated with CSF otorrhea but wouldn't typically cause a \"black eye\" or CSF rhinorrhea.\r\n\r\nHinge fracture occurs in the posterior aspect of the skull and is commonly associated with falls.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 242.","responses":[{"text":"Fracture through the anterior cranial fossa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gutter fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture through the posterior cranial fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hinge fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture through the middle cranial fossa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5674,"text":"APC/beta-catenin pathway is the hallmark of which of the following adenocarcinoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 296.","responses":[{"text":"Esophageal adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salivary gland carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostatic adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colorectal adenocarcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5676,"text":"A comatose patient was brought to the emergency (ER), whose pupils were contracted.  On examination, the pupil used to dilate initially by pinching the neck and slowly return to the original size. The person must have taken some toxic substance like:","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 545.","responses":[{"text":"Organophosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Barbiturate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbolic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Strychnine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5677,"text":"A 70-year-old patient presents with weakness, tiredness, and muscle cramps. The electrocardiogram (ECG) shows Q-T prolongation, flattening of T wave, and occasional A-V block. His serum K+ is low (2.8 mEq/L). He admitted to taking a laxative every day for the past several months. Which laxative drug could be responsible for the above condition?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Bisacodyl","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquid paraffin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bran","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcysteine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylcellulose","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5678,"text":"The commonest cause of chronic pancreatitis in Western countries is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 884.","responses":[{"text":"Alcohol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphincter of Oddi-stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypercalcemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tobacco","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5680,"text":"A 35-year-old male patient is planning a three-week trip overseas and asks for your advice regarding medications for traveler’s diarrhea. Which of the following drug is suitable for noninfectious travelers’ diarrhea?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 548.","responses":[{"text":"Mineral oil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoclopramide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphenoxylate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminum hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5682,"text":"A 35-year-old male patient was diagnosed with a peptic ulcer for the past 6 months. He is currently on maintenance therapy with H2 (histamine) receptor blockers along with a mucosal protective agent. Recently he complains of loss of libido and physical examination revealed signs of gynecomastia. Gynecomastia is the most common side effect of which of the following drug?","explanation":"*Cimetidine** is an H2 (histamine) receptor blocker used for the treatment of peptic ulcer disease. One of its notable side effects is **gynecomastia**, particularly with long-term use. The drug has **anti-androgenic effects**, which can lead to a loss of libido and gynecomastia in male patients.\r\n\r\nRoxatidine is another H2 receptor blocker used for the treatment of peptic ulcers. Gynecomastia is not a commonly reported side effect of this drug.\r\n\r\nFamotidine is yet another H2 receptor blocker. Although it shares a similar mechanism of action with cimetidine, it does not have the anti-androgenic effects that cimetidine possesses. As a result, gynecomastia is not a typical side effect of famotidine.\r\n\r\nOmeprazole is a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) used for the treatment of peptic ulcers and gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). Its mechanism of action and side effect profile are different from H2 blockers. It does not commonly cause gynecomastia.\r\n\r\nAluminum hydroxide is an antacid used to neutralize stomach acid. It can cause constipation as a side effect but does not typically cause gynecomastia.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Famotidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aluminum hydroxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Roxatidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cimetidine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5683,"text":"The gold standard test for diagnosis of celiac disease is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 806.","responses":[{"text":"Anti-endomysial antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoscopy with small bowel biopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-tissue transglutaminase antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-gliadin antibody","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5684,"text":"A comatose patient reports in the emergency department at Dow Hospital with suspected poisoning. On clinical examination, he has brownish oral mucosa and tongue, constricted pupil, and has passed greenish-brown urine in his trousers. What is the most likely cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 486.","responses":[{"text":"Carbolic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Morphine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulfuric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dhatura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cannabis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5685,"text":"Methods of investigation of the biliary system do not include:","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 853, 854, 855.","responses":[{"text":"ERCP (endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous pyelogram","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography or MRCP","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5689,"text":"A 26-year-old woman has had bloody, mucoid, low-volume diarrhea for the past six weeks. The stool frequency is five per day. She is afebrile, with no abdominal mass or tenderness. Stool examination reveals only mucous and blood with few leukocytes, no ova or parasites seen. Colonoscopy shows a friable, erythematous mucosa extending from the rectum to the middle of the descending colon. Rectal biopsy shows acute mucosal inflammation with cryptitis and crypt abscesses. Which of the following is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigellosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomembranous colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic colitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5690,"text":"A 27-year-male has a bout of profuse vomiting during a barbecue party. He complains of shortness of breath and severe lower chest pain and upper abdominal pain. On examination, he is tachypneic and tachycardia . There is rigidity of the upper abdomen. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Turner AR, Turner SD. Boerhaave syndrome. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 14, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430808/","responses":[{"text":"Perforated peptic ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Boerhaeve syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rolling hiatal hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5691,"text":"An 8-year-old boy had a sudden episode of nausea, vomiting, and profuse rice watery diarrhea. He developed dehydration, circulatory collapse, and anuria due to rapid loss of fluid and electrolytes. Which one of the following bacteria is most probably involved?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 181.","responses":[{"text":"Salmonella typhimurium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigella dysenteriae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterotoxigenic E.coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vibrio cholerae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Campylobacter jejuni","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5692,"text":"A 28-year-old lady falls from a scooter and gets minor abrasions on the arm and forearm and bruising of the scalp. After reaching home, she has a quarrel with her husband, receives mild blows on the face, and later dies. Autopsy reveals 100 ml of blood beneath a fractured skull at the site of the bruise. What is the probable cause of death?","explanation":"**Epidural hematoma** typically results from a traumatic injury, often associated with a fracture of the temporal bone. This can lead to rupture of the **middle meningeal artery**, causing blood to accumulate between the dura mater and the inner table of the skull. The classic presentation may include a **brief loss of consciousness (lucid interval)** followed by a **rapid decline in neurological status**, which could result in death if not treated promptly.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nSubarachnoid hemorrhage usually occurs due to the rupture of a cerebral aneurysm and would present with sudden, severe headache often described as the \"worst headache of my life.\"\r\n\r\nContusions refer to brain bruises and are more commonly seen in deceleration injuries. While contusions can be fatal, the presentation given does not fit the classic scenario of a contusion as the cause of death.\r\n\r\nSubdural hematoma results from the tearing of bridging veins between the dura and arachnoid. It typically presents with a more insidious onset and might not be the result of a mild blow or trauma.\r\n\r\nIntracerebral hemorrhage refers to bleeding within the brain parenchyma itself. It can be due to hypertension, vascular malformations, or other causes but does not align with the trauma and rapid decline in this patient.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 243.","responses":[{"text":"Subarachnoid hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracerebral hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subdural hematoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidural hematoma","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5693,"text":"A 30-year-old girl ingested an unknown substance and died. A post-mortem was carried out to find the cause of death. The oral cavity showed a diffuse grayish-white escharotic appearance. Also, the gastrointestinal (GI) tract was inflamed but the cecum and large intestine showed intense inflammation along with gangrene. What do you think is the probable substance she ingested?","explanation":"**Mercury** poisoning can result in a range of symptoms, and one of its effects when ingested in large amounts is the development of an **escharotic or corrosive effect** on the gastrointestinal mucosa. The presentation of an escharotic appearance of the oral cavity and the severe inflammation and gangrenous changes, especially in the cecum and large intestine, are consistent with mercury ingestion.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nArsenic poisoning typically causes symptoms like vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, and can cause QT interval prolongation on ECG. It does not typically cause the intense inflammation and gangrene as described.\r\n\r\nSilver ingestion or exposure can result in argyria, which is a blue-gray discoloration of the skin but does not cause the described gastrointestinal effects.\r\n\r\nLead poisoning can cause neurological symptoms, anemia, and abdominal pain, commonly referred to as \"lead colic,\" but it does not produce the described escharotic effects or the intense inflammation and gangrene in the cecum and large intestine.\r\n\r\nCopper poisoning can lead to hemolytic anemia, jaundice, and renal failure. It can cause gastrointestinal symptoms like vomiting and diarrhea but does not typically cause the described oral or gastrointestinal effects.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 496","responses":[{"text":"Mercury","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5694,"text":"A 30-year-old male patient comes into a rehabilitation center. He is an alcohol addict who wants to go for withdrawal treatment. What drug will you prescribe to this patient that will sensitize him to even a small dose of alcohol?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 620.","responses":[{"text":"Sodium floride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium bicarbonate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylpyrazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disulfiram","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5695,"text":"A 30-year-old man got hit on the vertex of the head that led to a fracture of the base of the skull. However, on examination, the bruise was found on the mastoid process behind the ears. What could be the reason for these positive findings of bruises on the mastoid processes?","explanation":"The presence of bruises on the mastoid processes (behind the ears) in a patient with a head injury involving a skull fracture is likely due to **gravitational shifting of blood.** \r\n\r\nIn cases of head trauma, particularly with skull fractures, blood can accumulate beneath the scalp, and its movement is influenced by gravity. As a result, blood can flow or shift to dependent areas, leading to the appearance of bruising or swelling in locations like the mastoid processes. This phenomenon is often referred to as **\"Battle's sign\"** when it occurs behind the ears and is associated with basilar skull fractures. It is a clinical sign that can be indicative of a skull fracture and may prompt further evaluation and imaging.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 400.","responses":[{"text":"Birth mark","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Due to natural disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vascularity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Color of skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gravitational shifting of blood","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5696,"text":"A 30-year-old man met a road traffic accident, while he was riding a bike. The collision made his body drag on the road before he stopped by hitting a nearby tree. On examination, he was found to have superficial injuries involving only superficial layers of skin. What is the most probable injury he has sustained?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 233.","responses":[{"text":"Bruises","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contusions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacerations","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abrasions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stabs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5710,"text":"A postgraduate surgical trainee has been asked to do closure of midline rectus sheath by the consultant. Which one of the following statements is correct in order to close the wound and avoid future hernias?","explanation":null,"reference":"Beeson S, Faulkner J, Acquista E, Hope W. Decreasing incisional hernia by teaching 4:1 suture to wound length ratio early in surgical education. Journal of Surgical Education. Published December 2021. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34642098/","responses":[{"text":"Length of the suture should be 3:1 of the wound length","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Length of the suture should be 5:1 of the wound length","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Length of suture should be 1:2 of the wound length","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Length of suture should be 1:1 of the wound length","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Length of suture should be 4:1 of the wound length","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5711,"text":"A 25-year-old man has noted cramping abdominal pain for the past week. On physical examination, there is right upper quadrant tenderness. Laboratory studies show increased serum transaminases. A liver biopsy was performed, and microscopic examination showed focal necrosis, interface inflammation with the extension of inflammation into the lobules from the portal triad. Which of the following is the most likely cause?","explanation":"The most likely cause of the patient's symptoms, including cramping abdominal pain, right upper quadrant tenderness, and increased serum transaminases is **viral hepatitis**. Histological findings of viral hepatitis include **focal necrosis** and **interface inflammation** with extension into the lobules from the portal triad.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 837.","responses":[{"text":"Toxic injury by drugs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eclampsia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral hepatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhoid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5730,"text":"A 30-year-old man underwent surgery for a road traffic accident, during which the surgeon notices the presence of a submucosal mass in the ileum. On microscopic examination, mass is composed of nests of cells with uniform round nuclei and cytoplasm with small purple granules. Immunohistochemical stain chromogranin is positive in these cells. Which of the following is most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 774.","responses":[{"text":"Melanoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoid tumor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoepithelioma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5732,"text":"A 35-year-old female presents to the outpatient department with obstructive jaundice. Her ultrasound showed stones in the common bile duct. What is the best management?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 839.","responses":[{"text":"Open bile duct exploration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lithotripsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stone dissolving medication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5734,"text":"A 35-year-old man comes to the emergency with complaints of severe abdominal pain and after evaluation, bowel perforation is suspected. His erect abdominal X-ray is performed. What is the most likely finding on an erect abdominal X-ray?","explanation":null,"reference":"Singh J, Steward M, Booth T, Mukhtar H, Murray D. Evolution of imaging for abdominal perforation. Annals of The Royal College of Surgeons of England. Published April 2010. Accessed July 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3080072/","responses":[{"text":"Free air","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Air-fluid levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calculi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcifications","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mural air","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5735,"text":"A 35-year-old man complains of pain in the abdomen for 3 months and nausea for 1 week. His stool sample is positive for occult blood. An upper GI endoscopy reveals normal esophageal mucosa, but a solitary 2 cm diameter shallow, sharply demarcated ulceration of the stomach is seen. Which of the following is most pertinent for this lesion?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 763.","responses":[{"text":"Potential for metastasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased gastric acid secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accompanying pancreatic gastrinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No need for biopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antral location","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5736,"text":"A 35-year-old woman who immigrated to the United States from Pakistan comes to the outpatient clinic complaining of anorexia, nausea, and abdominal pain. Lab investigations reveal a positive hepatitis-B surface antigen ( HBsAg). She is then started on therapy with Adefovir Dipivoxil. To avoid resistance with which of the following drugs can Adefovir Dipivoxil be used as adjuvant therapy?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1)Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 439. (2) 1.  Perrillo R, Schiff E, Yoshida E, et al. Adefovir dipivoxil for the treatment of lamivudine-resistant hepatitis B mutants. Hepatology (Baltimore, Md.). Published July 2000. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10869300/","responses":[{"text":"Ribavirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foscarnet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamivudine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Amantadine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Efavirenz","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5742,"text":"A 38-year-old man sitting on his terrace enjoying a cup of tea was suddenly hit on the head by a ricocheting glancing bullet that grazed his head and removed a part of the thickness of bone. What is this fracture called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 236.","responses":[{"text":"Depressed fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Communited fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gutter fracture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Indented fracture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5743,"text":"A 38-year-old businessman is on a trip to the United States where he develops diarrhea. He has to give a presentation in a few hours and needs rapid relief. He takes an antidiarrheal preparation containing loperamide. Which of the following is a property of loperamide that makes it useful in treating diarrhea?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 548.","responses":[{"text":"Anticholinergic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram-negative antibiotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sympathetic nervous system stimulant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibitor of myenteric plexus activity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Broad spectrum antibiotic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5744,"text":"A 38-year-old woman consults you before her planning to spend summer holidays in Gilgit and Swat with her husband and a 12-year-old boy. They never had hepatitis or liver disease in the past and none of them have had immunization against hepatitis. Which of the following plans would you recommend for the family?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston, Stuart H., et al., editors. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed., Elsevier, 2018: 873, 875.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis A and Hepatitis B vaccination for both parents and the child","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Screen parents for previous Hepatitis A infection, and recommend Hepatitis A vaccination for the child","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis A vaccination for both parents and child","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Screen all members of the family for Hepatitis A and B exposure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis A vaccination for parents and child and Hepatitis B vaccination for the child","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5745,"text":"A 40-year-old man who worked in the dye finishing industry for 20 years comes in with complaints of colic \u0026 bluish-black lines on the gums. Complete blood count along with peripheral smear shows anemia along with punctate basophilia in red blood cells. In the light of positive findings, what is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas, Gautam. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed., Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers, 2015: 501.","responses":[{"text":"Thallium poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silver poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mercury poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead poisoning","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5746,"text":"A 40-year-old female presents to the outpatient department with history of recurrent pain in right hypochondrium. Pain is aggravated with fatty meals. What is the mostly likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 887.","responses":[{"text":"Diverticulitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biliary colic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptic ulcer disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5747,"text":"A 42-year-old man comes with a history of chronic intake of alcohol. On examination, he has a firm liver that is not enlarged. CT scan reveals a cirrhotic liver. He is then sent to a rehabilitation centre to quit his drinking habit. In spite of complete abstinence from alcohol, he most likely remains at risk of developing which of the following diseases?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 419.","responses":[{"text":"Focal nodular hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiosarcoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocellular carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5748,"text":"A 43-year-old female develops severe epigastric and penetrating back pain following a dinner party. She was in shock when brought to the hospital. Which one of the following laboratory investigations would be most helpful in early diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 838, 839.","responses":[{"text":"Serum alkaline phosphatase levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper GI series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum aspartate aminotransferase level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum amylase level","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5749,"text":"A 43-year-old man complains of epigastric pain and nausea for 3 months. On physical examination, there are no abnormal findings. Upper GI endoscopy reveals a solitary sharply demarcated 2-cm shallow gastric ulcer at the antrum. Which of the following laboratory test findings is most relevant in this man?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 764.","responses":[{"text":"Positive anti-nuclear antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive urea breath test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated serum gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased plasma cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Achlorhydria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5780,"text":"A 45-year-old female is diagnosed with chronic cholecystitis due to cholelithiasis. What is the best treatment option?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 905.","responses":[{"text":"Analgesics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Laparoscopic cholecystectomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystostomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stone dissolving medications","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Open cholecystectomy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5781,"text":"A 50-year-old male presents with blood in the vomitus. There is no history of NSAIDs or steroids use. On examination, there is splenomegaly, caput medusa around the umbilicus, and positive shifting dullness. Given this history and examination, what is the most likely cause of upper GI bleeding?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 868, 869.","responses":[{"text":"Gastric or esophageal varices","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric neoplasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptic ulcer disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric angiodysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mallory Weiss tears","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5782,"text":"A 50-year-old male presents with his investigations showing HBsAg positive, HBeAg negative, ALT 120 IU/ml, and HBV DNA \u003e10,000 IU/ml. His fibro scan shows an F3 score. What is the best option to start with?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 876.","responses":[{"text":"Telbuvidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entecavir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pegylated interferon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamivudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adefovir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5783,"text":"A 50-year-old male presents with heartburn, epigastric pain, and regurgitation for 2 weeks. His examination is unremarkable. What is the treatment of choice?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 543.","responses":[{"text":"Bismuth subsalicylate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sucralfate plus H2 receptor antagonist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin, metronidazole, esomeprazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin, clarithromycin, omeprazole","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5784,"text":"A 55-year-old man with a history of ulcerative colitis for the last 20 years presents with a left iliac fossa mass. Which of the following can be the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Entero-enteral fistula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diverticulosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericolic abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entero-vesical fistula","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5785,"text":"A 55-year-old male presents to the emergency room with fever, chills \u0026 rigors. He has right hypochondrial pain and jaundice. What is the most appropriate diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 862.","responses":[{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pyelonephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholangitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5786,"text":"A 60-year-old male with small bowel diverticulosis presents with steatorrhea. He undergoes certain investigations including a hydrogen breath test which is positive. Which of the following condition should be considered in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 808.","responses":[{"text":"Bacterial overgrowth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroenteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tropical sprue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5787,"text":"A 60-year-old man with known ulcerative colitis presents with an acutely distended, tender abdomen. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 797.","responses":[{"text":"Adhesive obstruction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Toxic megacolon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intussusception","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal ulcer perforation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileal perforation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5788,"text":"A 60-year-old male presents with melena. Which of the following would be the most useful investigation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Wilson ID. Hematemesis, melena, and hematochezia. In: Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW, eds. Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations. 3rd ed. Butterworths; 1990. Accessed July 24, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK411/","responses":[{"text":"Flexible endoscopy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea breath test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool antigen for H pylori","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium swallow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Barium meal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5789,"text":"A blood relative of a patient with FAP (familial adenomatous polyposis) has a biopsy taken from a chronic polyp. Which of the following histological results is most likely?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 809.","responses":[{"text":"Hamartoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenomatous polyp","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Villous adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory polyp","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudopolyp","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5834,"text":"A child aged 3 years presents with congestion and is accidentally diagnosed as a case of chronic child abuse. What will the X-ray findings be?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Talus fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nobbing fracture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Greenstick fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overlapping of skull bones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spaulding sign","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5835,"text":"A patient presents with abdominal pain and frequent unsatisfactory bowel movements. For the last year, he has been using a purgative twice weekly to ease his bowel movements. On colonoscopy, the colon is found to be atonic with bluish pigmentation of the mucosa. Which is the most likely purgative that the patient has been using?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Gastrointestinal-II Module, Pharmacology, Topic: Drugs used in constipation.","responses":[{"text":"Bran","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ispaghul","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactulose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Senna","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liquid paraffin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5836,"text":"A patient presents with severe abdominal pain. Endoscopy reveals a benign ulcer in the antral mucosa. Select the drug that provides fastest relief from discomfort with a single dose:","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 541.","responses":[{"text":"Propantheline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antacids","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Omeprazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Misoprostol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H2 blockers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5838,"text":"A premature newborn has abdominal distention and several episodes of bloody diarrhea. What is the most likely diagnosis in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 141.","responses":[{"text":"Whipple's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Necrotizing enterocolitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reyes syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malabsorption","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5839,"text":"What is the state of complete emaciation called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 94.","responses":[{"text":"Malnutrition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malabsorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marasmus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic liver disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kwashiorkor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5840,"text":"A young boy got hit during a fight by a baseball bat. It was a blunt injury with a perpendicular impact which resulted in a linear opening of the skin overlying the scalp. It resembled an incised wound. What is your most probable diagnosis of the type of injury he has sustained?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 195.","responses":[{"text":"Split laceration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stretch laceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Avulsion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal laceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tear","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5842,"text":"A young girl is attacked by thieves who badly injure her with knives. On examination, the wounds are present on her body and arm, clearly cut with no bruising at the wound edges. Gaping is also noted at the edges. In light of the above findings, what is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"**Incised wounds** are typically characterized by **clean-cut, sharp edges**. They are often caused by sharp objects like knives or glass, and they tend to have minimal tissue damage beyond the immediate area of the cut. \r\n\r\n\r\nLacerations are wounds characterized by irregular, torn, or jagged edges. They are typically caused by blunt trauma, like a blow or a fall, where the skin and underlying tissue are forcefully stretched and torn. This differs from the clean-cut appearance described in the scenario.\r\n\r\nStab wounds are usually the result of a sharp, pointed object penetrating the skin. They often have a central entry point with less pronounced gaping compared to incised wounds.\r\n\r\nA contusion is essentially a bruise. Bruises result from blunt trauma that damages blood vessels beneath the skin, causing blood to leak into the surrounding tissue. They do not involve sharp-edged cuts or incisions.\r\n\r\nBruises are caused by blunt trauma that damages blood vessels, leading to the discoloration of the skin. They do not involve clear-cut, sharp edges or gaping.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 233.","responses":[{"text":"Stab wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incised wound","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bruise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Laceration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5850,"text":"A 29-year-old male presents to the outpatient department with a complaint of recurrent abdominal pain for the last 1 year, mostly in the lower abdomen that is relieved by defecation. He is also giving the history of increased frequency of stools approximately 3-4 times per day. He does not have weight loss \u0026 nighttime awakening due to these symptoms. On examination, he is vitally stable. Systemic and general physical examinations are unremarkable. Complete blood count and ESR are normal. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 796.","responses":[{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammatory bowel disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritable bowel syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Giardiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5853,"text":"A 3-week-old male is referred for persistent vomiting. He was well until 5 days ago but is now vomiting with each feed and is not putting on weight. After a test feed, he has projectile non-bilious vomiting. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 557.","responses":[{"text":"Ileal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyloric stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroesophageal reflux","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5863,"text":"A 32-year-old female presents with an altered level of consciousness and irritability for one day. On examination, she is pale and jaundiced. Her blood pressure is 160/100 mm Hg, pulse is 55 beats/min, respiratory rate is 32/min. Tender hepatomegaly is also present. On inquiry, she gives a history of yellow discoloration of sclera \u0026 skin for the last 7 days. Lab results show a hemoglobin level of 11.2 gm/dl, total white blood cell count of 12000/mm3, platelet level of 332,000/mm3. Liver function tests show total bilirubin of 15 mg/dl, direct bilirubin of 5 mg /dl, serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase of 3000 IU/L, alkaline phosphatase of 680 IU/L, prothrombin time of 60 sec, and International normalized ratio= 3.5. She is in grade 3 encephalopathy. The most common cause of this presentation will be?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 856, table 22.7.","responses":[{"text":"Viral hepatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Wilson's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetaminophen overdose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mushroom poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Budd-chiari syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5864,"text":"Antacid combinations of magnesium and aluminum salts are superior to single-component preparations because of which of the following reasons?","explanation":"Antacids that contain both magnesium and aluminum salts are often combined to counteract each other's potential side effects on bowel movements. **Magnesium-based antacids** tend to have a **laxative effect** and can lead to diarrhea, while **aluminum-based antacids** can result in **constipation**. \r\n\r\nWhen these two types of antacids are combined, their effects on bowel movements may balance out, reducing the likelihood of diarrhea or constipation.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 544.","responses":[{"text":"Single agents avoid gastric irritation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single agents are more likely alter bowel movement","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Single agents have rapid as well as sustained neutralizing action","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single agents are more likely to affect gastric emptying","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single agents avoid vomiting","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5865,"text":"Which of the following organisms cause bacillary dysentery?","explanation":null,"reference":"Yum LK, Agaisse H. Mechanisms of bacillary dysentery: lessons learned from infant rabbits. Gut Microbes. Accessed July 25, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7524307/","responses":[{"text":"Parasites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viruses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacteria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Unknown organisms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fungi","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5867,"text":"Barotrauma (spontaneous perforation) of the esophagus is classically seen in pressure events when a person strains against a closed glottis during?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kassem MM, Wallen JM. Esophageal perforation and tears. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 25, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532298/","responses":[{"text":"Defecation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Profuse vomiting","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Weight-lifting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Labor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glass blowing","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5877,"text":"Deterioration of fats and oils resulting in an unpleasant taste is termed as:","explanation":null,"reference":"Przybylski R, Wu J, Eskin NAM. A rapid method for determining the oxidative stability of oils suitable for breeder-size samples. Journal of the American Oil Chemists’ Society. Published 2013. Accessed July 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3690179/","responses":[{"text":"Fermentation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygenation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrogenation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rancidifcation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5912,"text":"A female patient comes to the clinic with complaints of diarrhea along with fever and abdominal cramping. Colonoscopy revealed pseudomembrane formation on colonic mucosa. The patient has a history of long-term intake of antibiotics. She still complains of repeated episodes of colitis. The doctor recommends fecal bacterio-therapy. Which one of the following bacteria is most probably involved?","explanation":"***Clostridium difficile*** is a bacterium responsible for causing antibiotic-associated colitis, including the **pseudomembranous colitis** seen in the patient. It typically occurs after a person has been taking antibiotics, which can disrupt the normal balance of gut bacteria. This disruption allows *C. difficile* to overgrow and produce toxins that lead to the characteristic symptoms of diarrhea, abdominal cramping, and fever.\r\n\r\nFecal microbiota transplantation (fecal bacterio-therapy) can be used as a treatment for recurrent *C. difficile* infection. It involves transplanting fecal matter from a healthy donor into the patient's colon to restore the normal balance of gut bacteria and eliminate the *C. difficile* infection. This therapy can be highly effective in cases of recurrent or severe *C. difficile*-associated colitis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 791.","responses":[{"text":"Clostridium perfringens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigella dysenteriae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacillus cereus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5913,"text":"What does free air under the diaphragm suggest?","explanation":"The presence of **free air under the diaphragm**, often seen on a medical imaging study like an X-ray or CT scan, is highly suggestive of **intestinal perforation**. When the wall of the gastrointestinal tract is compromised, such as in cases of a perforated ulcer, diverticulum, or other causes, air from within the digestive system can escape into the abdominal cavity. This air accumulates under the diaphragm, which is visible on imaging.\r\n\r\nIntestinal perforation can lead to a serious condition known as **peritonitis**, which is an inflammation of the peritoneum (the lining of the abdominal cavity). Immediate medical attention and surgical intervention are typically necessary in cases of intestinal perforation to address the underlying issue and prevent further complications.","reference":"Sureka B, Bansal K, Arora A. Pneumoperitoneum: What to look for in a radiograph? Journal of Family Medicine and Primary Care. Published 2015. Accessed July 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4535122/","responses":[{"text":"Paralytic ileus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ruptured liver abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal perforation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5914,"text":"Which one of the following is gastric carcinoid syndrome associated with?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 774.","responses":[{"text":"Zollinger Ellison syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"H pylori gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrophic gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Menetrier disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5915,"text":"Gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) is associated with a mutation of?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 775, 776.","responses":[{"text":"WT-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"p-53","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"p-63","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PDGFR-A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"PTEN","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5916,"text":"In a 35-year-old male acute pancreatitis is suspected. On taking history it's noted that the patient is an alcoholic. Which single lab investigation will you do to confirm the diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 839.","responses":[{"text":"ESR","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactate dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peptidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucosidase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5917,"text":"Which of these is most likely to cause a palpable gallbladder in a patient with jaundice?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 842.","responses":[{"text":"Carcinoma pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Choledocolithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Empyema of gallbladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucocele of gallbladder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5918,"text":"In a patient with pancreatitis, there is inappropriate release and activation of pancreatic enzymes, which destroy pancreatic tissue and cause the release of more enzymes. Which two laboratory blood tests are the most helpful in the evaluation of pancreatitis patients?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 839.","responses":[{"text":"H pylori antigen and antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amylase and LDH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LDH and CPK","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LFTs and lipase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipase and amylase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5919,"text":"The past and future trends of the population are determined through the population pyramid of a country in which field of demography?","explanation":null,"reference":"Juliano SA. Population dynamics. J Am Mosq Control Assoc. 2007;23(2 Suppl):265-275. Accessed July 25, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2442569/","responses":[{"text":"Population growth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zero growth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population momentum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Slow growth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population dynamics","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5920,"text":"Inflammatory bowel diseases include Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis. Which of the following is the best morphological feature to distinguish between the two diseases?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 800.","responses":[{"text":"Mucosal edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crypt abscesses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crypt distortion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoid aggregates in mucosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diffuse distribution of pseudopolyps","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5921,"text":"The mode of transmission of the hepatitis B virus is different in different parts of the world. Vertical transmission in 90% of cases is seen in high prevalence areas. However high-risk people are recipients of blood transfusions, dialysis patients, health care workers, I/V drug abusers, and homosexuals. Which of the following is the marker of infectivity in both acute and chronic cases of HBV infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 873.","responses":[{"text":"Anti-HB-c IgM","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HB-e antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HB-s antigen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti HB-e antibody","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti HB-c IgG","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5922,"text":"Which of these is the most common site of involvement in Crohn's disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 799.","responses":[{"text":"Rectum and stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach and caecum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caecum and appendix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach and small intestine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terminal ileum, ileocecal valve and cecum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5923,"text":"Protein malnutrition with edema in children leads to a condition called as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2020: 95.","responses":[{"text":"Kwashiorkor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goitre","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marasmus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5924,"text":"The only class of antiulcer drugs that can eradicate Helicobacter pylori and cure associated gastritis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 545.","responses":[{"text":"Antacids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colloidal bismuth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anticholinergic agents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H2 blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sucralfate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5925,"text":"Regarding carcinoma of the colon, which of these is the most appropriate investigation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 807.","responses":[{"text":"Fecal occult blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Double contrast barium enema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colonoscopy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CT abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5926,"text":"Which of these is the correct mechanism of action of omeprazole?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 543.","responses":[{"text":"Blockade of histamine (H2) receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockade of serotonin receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockade of gastrin receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockade of Na/K pump","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blockade of H/K pump","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5927,"text":"Select the prokinetic antiemetic drug which at relatively higher doses blocks both dopamine (D2) as well as serotonin (5-HT3 ) receptors and enhances acetylcholine release from myenteric neurons?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019. (2) Isola S, Hussain A, Dua A, Singh K, Adams N. Metoclopramide. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed July 25, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519517/","responses":[{"text":"Meclizine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prochlorperazine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Domperidone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoclopramide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cisapride","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5928,"text":"The process of collecting, compiling, and publishing demographic, economic, and social data pertaining to a specific time from all persons of a country is called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Gastrointestinal-II Module, Community Medicine, Topic: Demography-II.","responses":[{"text":"Demographic sample survey","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surveillance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Service statistics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Population census","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vital registration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5929,"text":"Which form of viral hepatitis is transmitted via contaminated food and water?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 836, table 18-3.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis A and E","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5930,"text":"Which form of intracranial hemorrhage is almost always traumatic in nature?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 243.","responses":[{"text":"Extradural","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pontine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracerebral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subdural","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subarachnoid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5931,"text":"Which of the following drugs is most likely to cause systemic alkalosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 544.","responses":[{"text":"Sodium bicarbonate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Methylcellulose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Castor oil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mineral oil","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5932,"text":"Which of the following tumors share major bulk in the large intestine?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 810.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphoepithelioma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Melanoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5983,"text":"While examining a victim, the medicolegal officer writes a medicolegal certificate by mentioning a wound exposing bone without a fracture on the occipital area. How is this injury classified?","explanation":null,"reference":"Pakistan penal code. Accessed August 3, 2022. https://pljlawsite.com/html/ppc337a.htm","responses":[{"text":"Shajjah - I - Ammah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Khafifah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Damigah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Munaquillah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah - I - Mudihah","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5984,"text":"Which of the following represents the percentage of nitrogen that is retained in the body after absorption of diet?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hoffman JR, Falvo MJ. Protein – which is best? J Sports Sci Med. 2004;3(3):118-130. Accessed July 25, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3905294/","responses":[{"text":"Biological value of proteins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycemic index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total protein in the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic pool of amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biological value of only essential amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15166,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of infections post-splenectomy?","explanation":"***Streptococcus pneumoniae*** is the most common pathogen responsible for **post-splenectomy infections** due to the spleen's role in filtering bacteria and mounting an immune response to **encapsulated organisms**.\r\n\r\nVaccination against *S. pneumoniae*, along with *Neisseria meningitidis* and *Haemophilus influenzae* type b (Hib), is recommended for splenectomy patients to reduce the risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI).\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n*N. meningitidis* and *H. influenzae* are also significant concerns post-splenectomy, but *S. pneumoniae* is the most common and concerning due to its prevalence and potential severity of infection.\r\n\r\nStaphylococcus aureus can cause infections in post-splenectomy patients, but it is not as common compared to the risks posed by encapsulated organisms like *S. pneumoniae*.","reference":"Tahir F, Ahmed J, Malik F. Post-splenectomy sepsis: a review of the literature. Cureus. Accessed January 26, 2023.\r\nhttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7059871/","responses":[{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemophilus influenza","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

